review_blob: UPDATED: JUL 15, 2015

Poured from a 750ml corked bottled. Surprising deep brownish red color that stops well before being black like you expect most chocolate coffee beers to be. Smells of raisins and cocoa with a hint of nuts. Mild coffee noted in the flavor along with fruit and raisin. Very unique and tastes.

Poured from a can a great golden color with a slight haze that quickly faded as the beer warmed, giving it great clarity. Smells crisp and grassy. Tastes of herbs, grass, and a bit of fruit. An absolutely wonderful, hop forward, easy drinking beer.

Had on draft in a small snifter. Balanced acidity hits your tongue right at the start that trails off into a fruitiness. It's bit like a framboise lambic but with more of a malt backbone. Absolutely delicious.

Poured (from a 22 oz bottle) a slightly cloudy, light golden color with a fine head that hung around virtually the entire time. Smells of mild hay. Has a bit of an astringent punch on the tongue as you taste it that mellows out to mild fruit and farm notes. A delicious beer.
Impressively clear golden color. Smells of berries and citrus. Very smooth on the tongue with a balanced bitterness. A good beer tip sip on a warm day.
Pours a deep brown. Tastes very rich and has a bit of sweetness against a strong roast character. It's delicious but isn't how I imagine brown ales.
beer_name: Cigar City Bolita Double Nut Brown Ale

review_blob: Poured from a 12 oz bottle, a deep black with a small, quickly disappearing head. Massive aroma of chocolate and peanut butter smells more like dessert than beer. Both carry through to the flavor along with a significant sweetness that makes it reminiscent of milk chocolate and a dry peanut butter. Body is nice and overall its definitely a fun, well done obscurity.

Pour from a 22 ounce bottle. Not sure of the age but am fairly confident its three months or less. Deep hazy copper color without much clarity out of the bottle, but it did noticeably clear a bit as it warmed. It has a nice hop aroma but is somewhat muted. Its bitter up front on the tongue and finishes with a lot of body and malt sweetness. A sipper.

Unique deep brown color that isn't opaque. Severe bitterness in the flavor that overcomes much of the roast notes, but they are there in the background. It's a good beer for sipping and I'm enjoying it.
beer_name: Founders Dark Penance Imperial Black IPA

review_blob: Amazing aroma knocked me over the head. I was enjoying it with the cup at arms length even. Dank with hints of citrus. It's a beautifully clear beer too. Sadly my pour was a little flat. Flavor is clean and crisp and surprisingly mild given the aroma.

A balanced milk stout, though my bottle seemed a little over carbonated to me. Thats really its only significant flaw though as I otherwise enjoyed it. The sweetness is just high enough to offset the roastiness. Im a bit confused as to the "Double Chocolate" deScription on the bottle though, as I wouldnt really consider it as being especially chocolate flavored. In fact, the only chocolate notes I feel are present are the same mild ones found in a lot of stouts and porters.
beer_name: Three Heads Sir Shock-A-Lot Double Chocolate Milk Stout

review_blob: Poured from a 750 ml bottle, deep black with a vigorous pillowy head that just sits there forever. Has a slight note of roast up front that quickly trails into some funky farmhouse notes and a very light body. A very interesting beer! Tastes very much like a Hennepin except with some roast. Im enjoying it.
beer_name: Ommegang Game of Thrones #5 - Three-Eyed Raven

review_blob: Pour from a 12 ounce bottle. Fine bubbled head and a slightly hazy golden color. Smells grassy and herby. Has a pleasant bitterness up from that is pronounced and coats the mouth. The aroma is the best part of this IPA, and overall, its a great one.

Draft. Interesting clean hop bitterness. It doesn't have those intense grassy notes I've become used to in IPAs. It kind of comes off as boring though. Am I comparing it to other beers too much? Probably. There's is definitely nothing wrong with it.

Hazy golden hue out of the bottle with a vigorous head that doesnt fade very quickly, leaving a nice lacing on the glass. Smells astringent and funky in a good way. Tastes boozy and has a slightly heavy mouthfeel. It reminds me of slightly moldy hay, and I dig it. A very unique beer, definitely worth trying.
Clean and light flowery hop aroma with a low but balanced bitterness. Sadly, it has some soapy undertones.
Interesting grapefruit flavor. It's so reminiscent of hops yet dryer and fruitier. I like it a lot but do find myself kind of craving a normal Sculpin.

Pleasant straw color with a slight, attractive haze. Has pleasant herb and flower notes up front on the flavor, but it trails to a slightly off putting mustiness. I have a bit of a hard time picking out the lilac flavor specifically but it definitely makes you think of flowers. A nice spring beer for Upstate New York.
Relatively unattractive milky brown color. Very strong maple flavor that comes off as artificial. Skip this one.
Served via nitro. Very smooth with a balanced roasted coffee flavor. Easy to drink. A great example of the style.

Its a deep brown color that definitely causes some confusion as you taste it. Its very dry on the palate and has herb flavors mixed with a clean bitterness. I like it. Its a great spring beer for those snowy upstate New York springs.

Poured from a bottle into a snifter. Slight orange in the aroma, not much else. Tastes of citrus up front that transitions into a slightly bitter dryness at the end. A very interesting beer. I could see myself sipping this with some asian food at dinner.
Pour from a keg in a tulip. Clean and light body with a great balance of malt and bitterness. This is a great, clean, easy drinking beer. I could drink a lot of it.
beer_name: Ninkasi Dawn of the Red India Red Ale

review_blob: Served from cask. A deep earthy sweetness up front that lingers as a pit of a floral hippiness comes to the front. Delicious but definitely a sipper. I would prefer a bit lighter body and cooler alcohol noted but Im enjoying it.

Pours a mostly clear, light gold with a moderate head. Smells most prominently of fruit and is quite inviting. Tastes like moderate pine up front and finishes quite dry on the palate. Honestly, I think one of the best reasons to drink this beer is the clever name (and all the snow currently outside), but its moderately refreshing regardless.
beer_name: Southern Tier Where The Helles Summer?

review_blob: Saison?! So confused. This beer pours dark with a chocolate milk head. Smells and tastes like thin mint Girl Scout cookies. So weird!
beer_name: Green Flash / St Feuillien  Friendship Brew Black Saison

review_blob: Beautiful deep copper color fitting to its name. Unexpectedly balanced for a big IPA but still has pleasant citrus and pine notes. I like it. Its possibly Stoneyards best beer yet.

Has a very strong aroma of green tea and grass. Its inviting though a little odd. Green tea is also very prevalent in the flavor but the hops back it up well. I very unique beer that also tastes great. Definitely worth seeking out.
beer_name: Baird / Ishii / Stone Japanese Green Tea IPA 10.1% (2015)

review_blob: Pours a deep and reddish amber with good clarity. Taste has citrus and pine up front and then trails off to a sweet maltiness. I'm really enjoying this one.
beer_name: Three Heads Buffalo Soul Jah Imperial Red Ale

review_blob: Very smooth on the tongue. More sweetness than I expected but it balances the coffee nicely. A great stout to have a whole pint of. Another wonderful beer from Stoneyard.

Beautiful deep Amber with great clarity. Sweet malt bomb in the flavor with a hint of booziness to balance it a bit. It's a rare treat at the Rohrbach brewpub and one of my favorites. Similar to Oskar Blues Old Chub but lighter body and cleaner.

Its so sweet! Wonderfully full body with a sweetness level and a hop level both so high it really is a unique experience. It reminds me a lot of an IPA mixed with a winter warmer and thats just fine. A wonderful seasonal that is actually on point with its season.

Wonderful pillowy head when poured. Super enticing. Aroma is mile fruitiness with some Belgian notes. Tastes of balanced bitterness with a slight citrus acidity. Overall very balanced and pleasant but not super unique.

Poured vigorously from a nitro widget can which captured that wonderful Guiness-like cascade that dissipated into a pleasant soft head. Beer smells of toffee and has a very smooth flavor. It's mild but it makes for a wonderful experience when you are just in the mood for some nitro body.

Aroma is very similar to other Ommegang beer: crisp, spicy, with a strange, non offensive hint of bologna. Spices come through in the flavor and its actually really pleasantly balanced. I was worried about a spice bomb and it isnt at all. Its kind of like a wintery version of Hennepin.
I was seriously worried I would be pouring this one down the drain but it is actually really nice. It achieves the stout flavors relatively nicely with coffee most prominent. I actually dig it.
beer_name: Stone Stochasticity Project Master of Disguise

review_blob: Very pleasant aroma, reminiscent of a cherry lambic. Initial flavor is strong and clean cherries with little else. Sadly, it trails off with an artificial edge similar to kids cough medicine. If you are looking for a strong fruit beer to go with something like a chocolate dessert it would probably pair well. On its own it's a bit strange...
Fresh and fruity aroma is nice and inviting. Has a nice malt balance with a small amount of must at the end. Pretty alright.
Poured deep black with a thickness to it. Some butter and roast in the flavor with very little bitterness. Doesn't taste overly boozy but coats the mouth. It's actually pretty balanced.

This beer has a bit of a strange chemical aroma. Its hard to describe it but its kind of like a faint nail polish remover smell. Very weird. Thankfully it doesnt carry through to the flavor at all. It has a nice rye spiciness with a piney hop back end. Probably my least favorite of the Box of Hops but its far from a bad beer.
beer_name: Ithaca Rustic Harvest Red Rye India Pale Ale

review_blob: Smells like grapes. Taste has fruit notes and a slightly odd bit of spice. I like it for its uniqueness. Definitely feels like a treat.

The brett is prominent in this one, something I didnt expect given its recent release. The aroma is amazing. Fruit characteristics mixed with a bit of cheese. Flavor isnt quite as good as it trails off into a bit of an unlikable mustiness. Overall though its a good beer.
Beautiful deep red color. Tastes of dried fruit with very little bitterness and a bit of booziness. A great example of a Belgian style.
beer_name: Ommegang Game of Thrones #4 - Valar Morghulis

review_blob: Very interesting beer. Lots of deep chocolate notes with a full body. Its pretty easy drinking. Im not sure I get any rye in the flavor but I imagine it is contributing to the body. I enjoy it. A great addition to Ithacas lineup.
A very pleasant and balanced east coast IPA. Doesn't have an overpowering hop aroma by any means with a nicely perceptible malt character. Wasabi is there via some timid spiciness at the end.
A great pumpkin beer for those that are turned off by absolute spice bombs. It's balanced but still clearly tastes as you'd expect. I enjoy it.

This is my absolute favorite higher alcohol / imperial pumpkin beer on the market. While the pumpkin pie spices are prevalent, they arent so huge as to cover up the great base beer thats there. A warming amount of booze combined with those spices really scream fall. Dont pass this one up.
Very very tart! Sour right from the get go and very delicious. It's called a sour stout and it looks it but tastes to me more like an extra sour Flanders brown.
Poured from a 22 ounce bottle with minimal to no head. Beautiful deep amber color. Caramel and raisin in the aroma. Tastes sweet with very low bitterness and a bit of butter.
